Quality issues¶

1- The date and time are objectives.¶

2- The time of purchase diveded to two columns: date and time in hours and seconeds.¶

3- The columns: branch, city, customer type, gender, and product line are objectives.¶

Tidiness issues¶

1- There is no hour of day, day of week, month name columns.¶

Data Cleaning¶

1- Convert branch, city, customer type, gender, and product line columns to category type¶

In [10]:
super_market['Branch'] = super_market['Branch'].astype('category')
super_market['City'] = super_market['City'].astype('category')
super_market['Customer type'] = super_market['Customer type'].astype('category')
super_market['Gender'] = super_market['Gender'].astype('category')
super_market['Product line'] = super_market['Product line'].astype('category')

2- Merge date and time columns¶

In [11]:
super_market["time"] = super_market["Date"] + " " + super_market["Time"]

3- Convert time column to datetime type¶

In [12]:
super_market['time'] = pd.to_datetime(super_market['time'])

4- create columns for purchase date in yyyy-mm-dd format, purchase hour of the day, purchase of week¶

In [13]:
super_market['purchase_time'] = super_market.time.dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
super_market['hour_ofday'] = super_market.time.dt.strftime('%H')
super_market['day_ofweek'] = super_market.time.dt.strftime('%A')
super_market['month_name'] = super_market.time.dt.month_name()

5- create category column for day type as weekend days or work days¶

In [14]:
super_market['WEEKDAY'] = pd.to_datetime(super_market['time']).dt.dayofweek 
super_market['day_type'] = 0          
super_market.loc[super_market['WEEKDAY'].isin([5, 6]), 'day_type'] = 'weekend'  # 5 and 6 correspond to Sat and Sun
super_market.loc[super_market['WEEKDAY'].isin([0, 1, 2, 3, 4]), 'day_type'] = 'work_days'
super_market['day_type'] = super_market['day_type'].astype('category')

6- Drop unused columns¶

In [15]:
super_market.drop(['purchase_time', 'WEEKDAY'], axis=1, inplace=True)

7- Create a column to count the the number of orders per city population¶

In [16]:
# create a list of the conditions 

conditions = [
    (super_market['City'] =='Yangon'),
    (super_market['City'] =='Mandalay'),
    (super_market['City'] =='Naypyitaw')
    ]

# create a list of the values we want to assign for each condition
values = [1/5.4, 1/1.5, 1/0.64]

# create a new column and use np.select to assign values to it using our lists as arguments
super_market['orders_per_pop'] = np.select(conditions, values)

8- Create a column to calculate number of items of each order per city population¶

In [17]:
conditions = [
    (super_market['City'] =='Yangon'),
    (super_market['City'] =='Mandalay'),
    (super_market['City'] =='Naypyitaw')
    ]

# create a list of the values we want to assign for each condition
values = [super_market['Quantity']/5.4, super_market['Quantity']/1.5, super_market['Quantity']/0.64]

# create a new column and use np.select to assign values to it using our lists as arguments
super_market['items_per_pop'] = np.select(conditions, values)

A- Univariate Exploration¶

What is the distribution of the number of orders, number of sold items, and gross income per branch?¶

In [20]:
plt.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize':(10,5), 'figure.dpi':100})
fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1, 3)
# Use the pie chart to describee the distribution of the number of orders for each branch
count = super_market.groupby('Branch')['Invoice ID'].count()
ax1.pie(count, labels = count.index, startangle = 90, autopct='%1.0f%%');
plt.axis('square');
ax1.set_title("Number of orders", fontsize= 10);

# Use the pie chart to describe the distribution of the number of orders for each branch
quantity_sum = super_market.groupby('Branch')['Quantity'].sum()
ax2.pie(quantity_sum, labels = quantity_sum.index, startangle = 90, autopct='%1.0f%%');
plt.axis('square');
ax2.set_title("Number of sold items", fontsize=10);

# Use the pie chart to describe the distribution of the gross income for each branch
gross_sum = super_market.groupby('Branch')['gross income'].sum()
ax3.pie(gross_sum, labels = gross_sum.index, startangle = 90, autopct='%1.0f%%');
plt.axis('square');
ax3.set_title("Gross income", fontsize=10);

plt.suptitle("KPIs per branch")
plt.show()

What is the distribution of the number of orders, andnumber of sold items w.r.t the population of the city of each branch?¶

In [21]:
plt.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize':(20,5), 'figure.dpi':100})
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2)

# Use the bar chart to describe the distribution of the number of purchases over months
order = ['A','B', 'C']
super_market.groupby('Branch')['orders_per_pop'].sum().loc[order].plot(kind='bar', ax=ax1)
ax1.set_title("Number of orders per million citizen", fontsize= 10);
ax1.set_xlabel('Branch', fontsize=10);
ax1.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=0)

# Use the bar chart to describe the distribution of the number of purchases over months
super_market.groupby('Branch')['items_per_pop'].sum().loc[order].plot(kind='bar', ax=ax2)
ax2.set_title("Number of sold items per million citizen", fontsize= 10);
ax2.set_xlabel('Branch', fontsize=10);
ax2.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=0)

Comment:¶

Although the number of orders and summation of sold items are almost the same for all branches, but by taking the city's population of each branch, the Branch C in Naypyitaw city has the highest performance.¶

In [39]:
#Creating bins for the customer's rating 
super_market['rating_bins'] = super_market['Rating'].apply(lambda x: 'Very Bad' if 0<x<=2
                                                  else 'Bad' if 2<x<=4
                                                  else 'Moderate' if 4<x<=6
                                                  else 'Good' if 6<x<=8
                                                  else 'Very Good' if 8<x<=10
                                                  else x);

plt.figure(figsize=[15, 7])
branch_prductline = super_market.groupby(['Branch', 'Product line']).mean()['Rating']
branch_prductline = branch_prductline.reset_index(name = 'average rating')
branch_prductline = branch_prductline.pivot(index = 'Product line', columns = 'Branch',
                            values = 'average rating')
sb.heatmap(branch_prductline, annot = True, fmt = '.3f',
           cbar_kws = {'label' : 'average rating'});
plt.title('The average rating for product lines per branch', fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Branchs', fontsize=15);
plt.ylabel('Product line', fontsize=15);

Comment:¶

Branch A: Although home and life-style products aquire the highest gross income for the branch, the rating for this line is below average. humman resources department should train the employee of this line to gain the satisfaction of customers¶

Branch B: Home and life style and sports and travel lines achieve very goog gross income and have the worst rating levels !!. HR department shoud train the employees to gain the satisfaction of customers¶

Branch C: Although the most customers are wonen, the home and life-style line shows a bad gross income, so some offers and new products may increase the purchases of this line. Also, it have a good rating performance for all product lines.¶
